Anonymous Mon 03 Jun 2024 00:13:12 No.66276811 Report

>>66276064
The logistics and leadership of battle scenes are things that are underrated in stories. Usually battles are written as Hollywood shoot em ups, but there is so much more going on. Imagine a siege like the one about to happen in the story, and try to wargame it out. Immediately you're gonna run into a series of questions you have to ask yourself:
>Where will the enemy attack from, and by extension, where should you build your fortifications?
>What kind of weapons does the enemy have access to?
>How many of the enemy are there?
>If the enemy attacks from multiple angles, how many of your men can be redirected to fend off the other group without causing your line to collapse?
>Will your troops break and run if it gets too intense? Will the enemy?
>Do they have saboteurs already in your ranks?
>Did they spike your supplies so your guns explode when you use them? Poison your food or water?
>Where will you treat the wounded while the fight is happening?
>Can you afford to keep reserves to repel flanking attacks/ reinforce certain parts of the line?
>How will you communicate to friends who are half a mile away if you don't have radios?
>Will the enemy just burn your crops outside the city, then wait you out?
>How is the enemy command structured, and how do they communicate? Can you intercept their comms, or even disrupt them by giving out fake orders?
Mind you, that's just the strategic end. On the front, a fighter has to wonder things like
>If they cover all the doors, and set my building on fire, wtf do I do?
>How do I deal with booby traps? Is the whole street mined or just this one spot? Do I have to go first to find out?
>If we bunch up, a machine gunner might wait for all of us to turn a corner into a cover less alleyway, then cut us down like a Normandy reenactment
>How do we know that our flanks are intact, and we aren't about to get shot in the back?
>Oh fuck our flank collapsed. Do we pull back, or will running out the back door get us all killed?

Hell, look at movies like ZULU. It was a small defence against a single rushing mob of spearmen (and a few snipers) but the defence in the siege was very fluid. Constantly the line had to be rearranged to make up for casualties. Wounded had to be removed from the hospital when it caught fire. Counterattacks had to be mounted in spots where the lines collapsed. Men had to run around giving ammunition to the soldiers who ran out. Barricades were moved, dead were moved, watches needed to be kept at night, ect ect.
The number one question that any commander should be asking at every single moment is "where the hell is everyone?".

For a concept like this, with inexperienced leadership and fighters, very few of these questions will be known in advance. They will be found out through trial and error. Trial and error of course meaning men dying in mass egregious casualties as they learn the hard way in Darwin's school of veterancy.
